\begin_layout Abstract
We develop a method of simulating the full quantum field dynamics of multi-mode
 multi-component Bose-Einstein condensates in a trap.
 We use the truncated Wigner representation to obtain a probabilistic theory
 that can be sampled.
 This method produces c-number stochastic equations which may be solved
 using conventional stochastic methods.
 The technique is valid for large mode occupation numbers.
 We give a detailed derivation of methods of functional Wigner representation
 appropriate for quantum fields.
 Our approach describes spatial evolution of spinor components and properly
 accounts for nonlinear losses.
 Such techniques are applicable to calculating the leading quantum corrections,
 including effects like quantum squeezing, entanglement, EPR correlations
 and interactions with engineered nonlinear reservoirs.
 By using a consistent expansion in the inverse density, we are able to
 explain an inconsistency in the nonlinear loss equations found by earlier
 authors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Wigner representation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wigner1932,Moyal1947,Dirac1945"

\end_inset

 is a convenient and effective method of simulating the dynamics of bosonic
 quantum fields
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drummond1993"

\end_inset

, including Bose-Einstein condensates (BECs)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Steel1998"

\end_inset

.
 It works best in the limit of large particle number, where third-order
 derivative terms in the Wigner-Moyal time-evolution equation can be truncated,
 and direct diagonalization approaches
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sakmann2009"

\end_inset

 become computationally impossible.
 Large particle number usually implies large numbers of field modes with
 significant population, which makes two-mode variational approaches
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Li2008,Li2009,Sinatra2011"

\end_inset

 less accurate.
 This technique has been applied to a number of quantum dynamics problems
 in both quantum optical
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drummond1993a,Corney2008,Corney2006"

\end_inset

 and BEC systems, including fragmentation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Isella2006,Isella2005,Gross2011"

\end_inset

, dissipative atom transport
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ruostekoski2005"

\end_inset

, dynamically unstable lattice dynamics
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shrestha2009"

\end_inset

, dark solitons
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Martin2010,Martin2010a"

\end_inset

, turbulence
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Norrie2005,Norrie2006a"

\end_inset

, decoherence
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Egorov2011"

\end_inset

, and squeezing
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Opanchuk2012,Opanchuk2012a"

\end_inset

.
 A comparison of theoretical predictions of quantum fluctuations with experiment
 has generally resulted in excellent agreement, provided the large particle
 number criterion is met
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Corney2006,Deuar2007"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The truncated Wigner technique is a numerically robust and useful method
 for BEC simulations.
 Other methods such as the positive-P representation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drummond1980"

\end_inset

 are known to work better
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Deuar2007"

\end_inset

 when the truncation approximation breaks down, and there are a number of
 studies of applicability that compare the truncated Wigner method with
 the exact positive-P method
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chaturvedi2002,Dechoum2004"

\end_inset

 or, where feasible, Bloch-basis approaches.
 The typical result found is that the truncated Wigner method gives correct
 results out to a characteristic break time.
 At this stage, the accumulated errors can lead to large discrepancies in
 quantum correlations.
 The method is weakest when dealing with nonlinear quantum tunneling
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drummond1989,Kinsler1991a"

\end_inset

, which depends on both long time dynamics and quantum correlations.
 Within its domain of applicability the technique is remarkably accurate
 and stable.
 The overall picture of how this method is related to other techniques for
 quantum dynamics has been recently reviewed
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "He2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The phase-space treatment of multimode problems can be simplified by working
 with functional mappings to field operators rather than to single-mode
 operators.
 This approach was initially introduced by Graham
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Graham1970,Graham1970a"

\end_inset

.
 Later it was used in a number of works
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Steel1998,Gardiner2003,Isella2006,Norrie2006a,Blakie2008"

\end_inset

 without formally defining the corresponding transformations or accompanying
 theorems; a more detailed description was given by Polkovnikov
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Polkovnikov2010"

\end_inset

.
 In order to calculate the approximate evolution of the Wigner function
 of a system numerically, one has to truncate third-order derivative terms
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drummond1993,Steel1998,Sinatra2002"

\end_inset

, and project out modes with low occupation numbers.
 This further complicates the formal description of the method.
 Recent developments in ultra-cold atomic physics mean that processes like
 nonlinear damping, not considered in detail previously, have also become
 important.
 Accordingly, much of the mathematical derivation of these techniques is
 not readily available.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper we present a formal description of the application of the
 resulting truncated Wigner representation to simulating the multi-mode
 dynamics of Bose-Einstein condensates (BECs).
 We successively reduce the problem in its initial form, the master equation
 for bosonic field operators, to a system of stochastic differential equations,
 which have significantly lower computational complexity.
 While there is a price for making the truncation approximation, we emphasize
 that this is a systematic expansion in a small parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the particle number.
 Such expansions are also relevant to stochastic diagram techniques
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chaturvedi1999"

\end_inset

, which can be used to formally calculate order-by-order behaviour in such
 equations.
 Although not treated here in detail, our identities can be applied to parametri
c interactions, where the truncation approximation has also been applied
 to EPR and entanglement problems and compared to more rigorous positive-P
 simulation methods
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chaturvedi2002,Dechoum2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of this paper is to provide a more rigorous proof, within the
 functional analysis formalism, of several identities that are used for
 these derivations.
 We focus especially on the problem of nonlinear damping.
 This is a dominant relaxation mechanism in BEC systems, and is often ignored
 or (incorrectly) approximated using linear loss terms.
 We derive the correct Fokker-Planck drift and noise terms for general multicomp
onent damping using the 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

 expansion, which transforms to an expansion in the inverse particle density
 for quantum fields.
 Even in the single-component case, the drift term has both a leading (classical
) term and a quantum noise correction to the damping.
 This is needed to predict the loss behaviour correctly, and is important
 in high-accuracy simulations.
 Such corrections — both in the drift and noise — are relevant to topics
 like EPR correlations, entanglement and quantum squeezing in the presence
 of nonlinear reservoirs, a topic of increasing importance in areas ranging
 from quantum optics and BEC physics to nanomechanical oscillators
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chaturvedi1977,Reid1986a,Rabl2004"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We derive the resulting stochastic differential equations from the functional
 Fokker-Planck equations, and show when the corresponding truncation approximati
ons are applicable.
 The final equations can be treated using standard computational techniques
 for solving ordinary and partial stochastic differential equations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drummond1990,Werner1997,Wilkie2005"

\end_inset

.
 There are code generator packages and public domain websites with code
 available for this purpose
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Collecutt2001,Dennis2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quantum fields and dynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper we consider a 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

-component Bose gas in 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 effective dimensions.
 The Hamiltonian for this system is expressed in terms of bosonic field
 creation and annihilation operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Psi}_{j}^{\dagger}(\boldsymbol{x})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Psi}_{j}(\boldsymbol{x})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1\ldots C$
\end_inset

, which obey standard bosonic commutation relations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[\hat{\Psi}_{j},\hat{\Psi}_{k}^{\prime\dagger}]=\delta_{jk}\delta(\boldsymbol{x}^{\prime}-\boldsymbol{x}).\label{eqn:master-eqn:commutators}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{D}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional coordinate vector, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Psi}_{j}\equiv\hat{\Psi}_{j}(\boldsymbol{x})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Psi}_{k}^{\prime}\equiv\hat{\Psi}_{k}(\boldsymbol{x}^{\prime})$
\end_inset

 for brevity (the same abbreviation will be used for all functions of coordinate
s), and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(\boldsymbol{x}^{\prime}-\boldsymbol{x})$
\end_inset

 is a D-dimensional Dirac delta function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quantized Hamiltonian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second-quantized Hamiltonian for the system, integrated with a 
\begin_inset Formula $D-$
\end_inset


