\begin_inset Formula $U_{kj}=U_{jk}$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{W}\left[[\int d\boldsymbol{x}\frac{U_{jk}}{2}\tilde{\Psi}_{j}^{\dagger}\tilde{\Psi}_{k}^{\dagger}\tilde{\Psi}_{j}\tilde{\Psi}_{k},\hat{\rho}]\right] & = & \int d\boldsymbol{x}U_{jk}\left(\frac{\delta}{\delta\Psi_{j}}\left(-\Psi_{j}\Psi_{k}\Psi_{k}^{*}+\frac{\tilde{\delta}_{k}}{2}(\delta_{jk}\Psi_{k}+\Psi_{j})\right)\right.\nonumber \\
 &  & \left.+\frac{\delta}{\delta\Psi_{j}^{*}}\left(\Psi_{j}^{*}\Psi_{k}\Psi_{k}^{*}-\frac{\tilde{\delta}_{k}}{2}(\delta_{jk}\Psi_{k}^{*}+\Psi_{j}^{*})\right)\right.\nonumber \\
 &  & \left.+\frac{\delta}{\delta\Psi_{j}}\frac{\delta}{\delta\Psi_{j}^{*}}\frac{\delta}{\delta\Psi_{k}}\frac{1}{4}\Psi_{k}-\frac{\delta}{\delta\Psi_{j}}\frac{\delta}{\delta\Psi_{j}^{*}}\frac{\delta}{\delta\Psi_{k}^{*}}\frac{1}{4}\Psi_{k}^{*}\right)W.\label{eqn:truncation:nonlinear-term}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Loss terms
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eqn:master-eqn:loss-term"

\end_inset

) are transformed with Theorem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:transformations:w-losses"

\end_inset

 and result in a similar equation, with a finite number of differential
 terms up to order 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n-$
\end_inset

body collisional losses.
 It should be recalled that in the above equation, the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\delta}_{j}\equiv\delta_{\mathbb{M}_{j}}(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{x})$
\end_inset

 was introduced previously for brevity; in general this is a cut-off dependent
 constant with units of density.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{jk}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{jk}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{\boldsymbol{l}}$
\end_inset

 are real-valued, all the transformations described above result in a partial
 differential equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial W}{\partial t}=\int d\boldsymbol{x}\left\{ -\sum_{j=1}^{C}\frac{\delta}{\delta\Psi_{j}}\mathcal{A}_{j}-\sum_{j=1}^{C}\frac{\delta}{\delta\Psi_{j}^{*}}\mathcal{A}_{j}^{*}+\sum_{j=1}^{C}\sum_{k=1}^{C}\frac{\delta^{2}}{\delta\Psi_{j}^{*}\delta\Psi_{k}}\mathcal{D}_{jk}+\mbox{O}\left[\frac{\delta^{3}}{\delta\Psi_{j}^{3}}\right]\right\} W.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Terms of order higher than 2 are produced both by the nonlinear term in
 the Hamiltonian and loss terms.
 Such an equation could be solved perturbatively if there were only orders
 up to 3 (which means an absence of nonlinear losses)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Polkovnikov2003"

\end_inset

, but in most cases all terms except for first- and second-order ones are
 truncated.
 In order to justify this truncation in a consistent way, we develop an
 order-by-order expansion in 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N_{c}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{c}$
\end_inset

 is a characteristic particle number in a physical interaction volume, and
 truncate terms of formal order 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N_{c}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This is achieved
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drummond1993"

\end_inset

 by use of the formal definition of a scaled Wigner function 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\psi}$
\end_inset

, satisfying a scaled equation in terms of dimensionless scaled fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

, with: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\psi_{j} & = & \Psi_{j}\sqrt{\ell_{c}^{D}/N_{c}}\nonumber \\
\mathcal{A}_{j}^{\psi} & = & t_{c}\sqrt{\ell_{c}^{D}/N_{c}}\mathcal{A}_{j}+\mbox{O}\left(1/N_{c}^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
\mathcal{D}_{jk}^{\psi} & = & t_{c}\left(\ell_{c}^{D}/N_{c}\right)\mathcal{D}_{jk}+\mbox{O}\left(1/N_{c}^{2}\right).
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{c}$
\end_inset

 is a characteristic interaction time and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{c}$
\end_inset

 is a characteristic interaction length.
 These would normally be chosen as the healing time and healing length respectiv
ely in a BEC calculation.
 Typically the cell size is chosen as proportional to the healing length,
 for optimum accuracy in resolving spatial detail.
 Using this expansion, a consistent order-by-order expansion in 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/N_{c})$
\end_inset

 can be obtained, of form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial W^{\psi}}{\partial\tau}=\int d\boldsymbol{x}\left\{ -\sum_{j=1}^{C}\frac{\delta}{\delta\psi_{j}}\mathcal{A}_{j}^{\psi}-\sum_{j=1}^{C}\frac{\delta}{\delta\psi_{j}^{*}}\mathcal{A}_{j}^{\psi*}+\sum_{j=1}^{C}\sum_{k=1}^{C}\frac{\delta^{2}}{\delta\psi_{j}^{*}\delta\psi_{k}}\mathcal{D}_{jk}^{\psi}+\mbox{O}\left[\frac{1}{N_{c}^{2}}\right]\right\} W^{\psi}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the assumption of the state being coherent, the simple condition for
 truncation — i.e., omitting terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $O(1/N_{c}^{2})$
\end_inset

 — can be shown to be
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sinatra2002"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{j}\gg|\mathbb{M}_{j}|,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the total number of atoms of the component 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 The inclusion of the mode factor is caused by the fact that the number
 of additional terms increases as the number of modes increases, which may
 be needed to treat convergence of the method for large momentum cutoff.
 We see immediately that there are subtleties involved if one wishes to
 include larger numbers of high-momentum modes, since this increases the
 mode number while leaving the numbers unchanged.
 In other words, the truncation technique is inherently restricted in its
 ability to resolve fine spatial details in the high-momentum cutoff limit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N_{c}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to an expansion in the inverse density, which requires the
 inequality
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Norrie2006"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\delta}_{j}=\delta_{\mathbb{M}_{j}}(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{x})\ll|\Psi_{j}|^{2}.\label{eqn:truncation:delta-condition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The coherency assumption does not, of course, encompass all possible states
 that can be produced during evolution, which means that the condition above
 is more of a guide than a restriction.
 For certain systems the truncation was shown to work even when
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eqn:truncation:delta-condition"

\end_inset

